# Marker file for .github/workflows/dns-watch.yml

When DNS for armybots.ru first resolves to 45.12.73.106 on both
Google (8.8.8.8) and Cloudflare (1.1.1.1) public resolvers, the
workflow:

  1. Sends a Telegram message to ADMIN_CHAT_ID via BOT_TOKEN_NOTIFICATIONS.
  2. Creates the file `.dns-notified` (no extension) in the repo root.
  3. Commits and pushes that file to main.

On every subsequent run the very first step checks whether `.dns-notified`
exists; if yes — the workflow exits silently without resolving DNS or
sending anything. This is the idempotency mechanism that prevents
duplicate notifications.

## How to re-test the notification flow

If you ever need to fire a new "DNS propagated" Telegram message
(for example, after migrating to a different IP or for a manual smoke
test):

  1. Delete the marker on main:
       git rm .dns-notified && git commit -m "dns: reset marker" && git push
  2. Trigger the workflow manually:
       gh workflow run dns-watch.yml --repo pohilkom89-ctrl/army-bot
  3. Watch:
       gh run watch --repo pohilkom89-ctrl/army-bot

If both resolvers currently return 45.12.73.106 the message will fire
again and a fresh `.dns-notified` will be committed.

## Why this file exists

This `.dns-notified.example` is a permanent doc fixture; the actual
runtime marker is `.dns-notified` (no `.example` suffix) and is created
automatically by the workflow on first success. Don't edit `.dns-notified`
by hand — only delete it via `git rm` if you want to re-arm the workflow.
